n each exposure of DESI.</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The LIneA Science Server being made available at NCSA and which will be used as one of the interfaces of the DES data release DR1.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In addition, LIneA maintains a data center (1000 cores processing cluster, 1 PB mass storage and a host of other machines) for its affiliates, currently around 80 members, a mirror site for SDSS providing independent SkyServer and CasJobs services, and provides support to the computer infrastructure being used by the APOGEE-2 project at the Las Campanas Observatory.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">LIneA is funded by MCTIC, FINEP and </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Fundação de Amparo à Pesquisa do Estado do Rio de Janeiro</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> - </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">FAPERJ</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span>\r\n\r\n<b><i>About the LIneA Science Server Interface</i></b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Currently the LIneA Science Server provides access to the following services:</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sky viewer: display a panoramic view of DES images across its footprint.</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Target viewer: visualize and manage list of objects. One can rank,  reject entries filter by properties, and create mosaics.</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Science products: browse scientific products produce by LIneA Science portal or DES collaboration, such as maps, VACs, and cluster catalogs.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the future we expect it to also provide</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">User query: write SQL queries in a web interface to get information from DES NCSA database.</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Catalog builder: build a catalog using the framework presented in Fausti et al.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b><i>Credits</i></b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We would like to thank the contribution of the following people and organizations:</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">NCSA team for providing the infrastructure and tools such as which are use by Science Server </span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">E. Bertin for the use of  VisiOmatic and for helping in its installation</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">P. Fernique for helping in the integration of Aladin in the Science Server framework</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">LIneA team:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Luiz Nicolaci da Costa (Lead Scientist)</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Angelo Fausti Neto (Technical Lead)</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Glauber Costa</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Riccardo Campisano</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Rafael Brito</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Fabio Oliveira</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Felipe Machado </span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ricardo Ogando</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Guilherme Soares</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cida Silveira</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Maria Luiza Sanchez</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Humberto Aranha</span></li>\r\n</ul>','About us','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2017-09-18 16:56:06','2017-09-18 19:56:06','',92,'https://desportal.cosmology.illinois.edu/dri/apps/home/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(150,1,'2017-09-19 16:24:19','2017-09-19 19:24:19','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This is the release of beta version release of the LIneA Science Server which is a modernized version of the system running at Fermilab since 2014.  The main goals of this development was to introduce newer technology using the extJS framework with django instead of turbogears, each tool is independent facilitating deployment of new features and bug fixes, and easy access to images and catalogs by making it available at NCSA.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As announced to the collaboration the Fermilab version was frozen in January 2016, while a preliminary version of the new system has been running at NCSA since June 2016 to enable people to visualize the data from Y3 with the last update taking place 06/14/2017.  Since then 631 commits have been made, 1752 files modified, 54708 lines added and 160646 removed involving a number of people in LIneA´s IT team. A complete list of in-house and external contributors can be found in </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">About us</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> section.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The current version is for the use of the DES collaboration members and following tools are available: sky viewer, target viewer and science products. These are the ones intended to become available for the general public in December but connected to separate tables been created by the NCSA team. In parallel, we are also developing user query an upgraded version of the one available at Fermilab but scarcely used which will be integrated to the Target Viewer greatly simplifying the life of the user.  In a longer timescale is also envisioned the deployment of  a catalog builder tool using the infrastructure developed for the Science Portal and presented in the last portal review (DES-doc-10898-v1) and part of the paper Fausti et al  (DES-doc-9416-v9). </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The current system is still a work in progress and we call on users to provide feedback to the team using the contact us form which will send a classified ticket to LIneA´s helpdesk facilitating tracking them down. We hope that this will allow us to shake down bugs in preparation for the public release next December. We will also continue to improve the tutorial videos by including some text, updating some of them and including new ones to cover all the features normally used.</span>\r\n\r\nThere are some known bugs or inconvenient features:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>We have implemented a social log in to serve as an example of what will be used in the public release. Currently, for tests we keep a white list to prevent access from unauthorized users;</li>\r\n 	<li>The number of objects in a list is not correct The quick upload only works if the format of the example is used even minor departures will cause an error</li>\r\n 	<li>We are aware of problems handling objects close to ra =0</li>\r\n 	<li>We are currently limiting the number of cutouts to tem to serve as an example</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese problems are currently being addressed by our team and we expect to have another quick release as soon as possible. As soon as the environment becomes a bit more stable more tutorial videos will be produced.','Preliminary Release of the LIneA Science Server','','publish','open','open','','preliminary-release-of-the-linea-science-server','','','2017-09-25 14:18:31','2017-09-25 17:18:31','',0,'https://desportal.cosmology.illinois.edu/dri/apps